title: Baylor, TCU lead NCAA 1-128 Re-rank, but tough times loom
text:
Utah's loss at Southern California drops the Utes from No. 2 in the USA TODAY Sports 1-128 Re-rank to outside the top 10, leaving the top spots in this week's list to a pair of fierce rivals from the Big 12 Conference. Baylor leads the way, though quarterback Seth Russell's neck injury is a looming concern as the Bears prepare for a difficult November. Next comes TCU, which has been dealing with injuries woes of its own throughout the regular season.
Follow the road to the 2015 College Football Playoff at The Football Four , our home to rate and debate the nation's best. Utah's slide makes No. 9 Stanford the top-ranked team from the Pac-12 Conference. Stanford wouldn't face the Utes until the Pac-12 title game, but the Cardinal have games against Oregon, California and Notre Dame in November. While other conferences feast on each other — Michigan State plays Ohio State and LSU plays Alabama in the coming weeks — the Cardinal are in prime position to secure a place in the College Football Playoff.
Once again, the Re-rank is defined by the parity seen across the top leagues in the Football Bowl Subdivision. Twenty-four teams enter the final stretch of the season with one or fewer losses. The American Athletic Conference alone has three unbeaten teams: No. 11 Memphis, No. 16 Temple and No. 23 Houston. The Owls' quest for perfection faces its toughest test in Saturday night's matchup against Notre Dame.
New to the top 25: UCLA and Georgia.
Out of the top 25: Texas A&M and California.
